}


=> Without rollbackFor = Exception.class, => only runtime exceptions trigger a rollback by default.

=> With rollbackFor = Exception.class, => all exceptions (checked and unchecked) cause rollback.

=> Transactions only commit if the method completes successfully without any exceptions.


```
@Transactional
public void saveUsers() throws IOException {
   ...
   if (someCondition) {
       throw new IOException("File not found");
   }
}
```

=> By default, no rollback will  happen for above method beacuse IOException is a checked exception.

=> To make rollback work for such checked exceptions, you must write: 

		@Transactional(rollbackFor = IOException.class)

